a. The MultiPixel Governance Framework — including all folders, files,
   subfolders, documents, standards, policies, procedures, and rules
   contained within the “Governance” directory of the official MultiPixel
   repository — is hereby incorporated by reference into this License and
   forms a legally binding part of it.

b. All Users, Mod creators, Server operators, and any party interacting
   with the Software are required to comply with all Governance documents
   in full.

c. All Governance documents must include a clear version number
   (e.g., “Governance v1.4”). Users are bound to the version in effect at
   the time they use the Software or operate a Server or Mod.

d. MultiPixel will maintain a public changelog of Governance updates. Each
   update will specify its version number and effective date.

e. Except for emergency security updates, all Governance updates take
   effect thirty (30) days after being posted. Continued use of the
   Software after the effective date constitutes acceptance of the updated
   Governance version.

f. Emergency updates addressing security, safety, or legal compliance may
   take effect immediately upon posting. MultiPixel will identify such
   updates clearly in the changelog.

g. In the event of any conflict between this License and any Governance
   document:
      i. This License governs broad rights, restrictions, and ownership.
     ii. The Governance documents govern detailed requirements, technical
         standards, operational rules, compliance procedures, and
         enforcement mechanisms.

23. Severability

If any provision is invalid, the rest remains in effect.

24. Mod Approval Requirements

a. All Mods must be submitted for approval before they may be uploaded,
   shared, distributed, published, monetized, or used on any public Server.
   No Mod may bypass the approval system.

b. All Mods require approval regardless of size, purpose, content,
   complexity, monetization status, or distribution method. This requirement
   exists to prevent malware, backdoors, unauthorized telemetry, exploits,
   unsafe content, prohibited monetization, and impersonation of official
   features.

c. Mods are reviewed under different risk tiers, including fast‑track
   cosmetic reviews, standard gameplay reviews, and full reviews for
   monetized, networked, data‑collecting, political, or engine‑altering
   Mods.

d. All Mod submissions must include required information such as Mod name,
   description, category, files, source code (if applicable), changelog,
   monetization details, data‑collection details, safety considerations,
   and developer identity.

e. Mods will be automatically denied if they contain malware, backdoors,
   unauthorized telemetry, undisclosed data collection, gambling systems,
   crypto/NFT monetization, extremist content, hate speech, sexual content
   involving minors, attempts to bypass engine security, or attempts to
   impersonate official MultiPixel content.

f. Approval outcomes may include approval, conditional approval, denial,
   return for revision, or suspension pending investigation.

g. Approval may expire if the Mod is not updated for major engine versions,
   changes ownership, introduces new monetization or data collection, or
   undergoes major redesign. Renewal requires resubmission and updated
   compliance review.

h. Distributing or operating a Mod without approval is a severe violation
   and may result in removal from the Mod Marketplace, monetization bans,
   delisting, legal action, or license termination.

i. Developers are strongly encouraged to use official MultiPixel inbuilt
   systems for data handling, telemetry, storage, transmission, and
   analytics to ensure compliance and reduce audit requirements. Third‑party
   services may be approved only under strict conditions.

j. All Mods must comply with the latest version of the Mod Approval
   Requirements.

25. Mod Audit Requirements

a. All Mods may be audited at any time. Developers must fully cooperate
   with all audit requests, including providing required materials,
   documentation, and information. Audits ensure compliance with safety,
   data, monetization, and content rules.

b. MultiPixel may conduct routine audits, triggered audits, or full
   investigative audits. Triggered or investigative audits may occur in
   response to user reports, suspicious behavior, unusual data or
   monetization patterns, performance anomalies, or suspected violations.

c. The scope of an audit may include review of source code, compiled code,
   assets, data collection behavior, telemetry behavior, monetization
   systems, sponsorships, network traffic, performance, content, safety
   compliance, documentation, and server‑side integrations.

d. Developers must provide all required materials upon request, including
   source code (if applicable), binaries, assets, documentation, data
   collection details, telemetry configuration, monetization configuration,
   sponsorship agreements, update logs, version history, and integration
   details. Failure to provide complete and accurate information is a
   severe violation.

e. Audit outcomes may include findings of compliance, compliance with
   warnings, minor non‑compliance, major non‑compliance, or severe
   violations. Enforcement actions follow the Mod Violation and Penalty
   systems referenced in Section 15.

f. A Mod may be immediately suspended if malware, backdoors, unauthorized
   telemetry, undisclosed personal data collection, extremist content,
   sexual content involving minors, gambling systems, crypto/NFT systems,
   pay‑to‑win systems, or attempts to bypass security, approval, or audits
   are detected. Suspension is immediate and non‑negotiable.

g. If violations are found, developers must fix issues, resubmit updated
   versions, provide updated documentation, and undergo follow‑up audits if
   required. Failure to remediate may escalate penalties.

h. Audit details are confidential between MultiPixel and the developer,
   except that enforcement actions such as removals, suspensions, or bans
   may be made public.

i. Refusal to cooperate with an audit constitutes a severe violation and
   may result in immediate suspension, removal from the Mod Marketplace,
   permanent bans, legal action, or license termination.

j. Developers are strongly encouraged to use official MultiPixel inbuilt
   systems for data handling, telemetry, storage, transmission, and
   analytics to reduce compliance risk and simplify audits. Third‑party
   systems may be approved only under strict conditions.

k. All Mods must comply with the latest version of the Mod Audit
   Requirements.

26. Mod Compliance Requirements

a. All Mods must comply with this License, all safety standards, all data
   and telemetry rules, all monetization rules, all content restrictions,
   all audit requirements, and all technical and operational requirements
   established by MultiPixel. Mods must maintain compatibility, stability,
   and security at all times.

b. Mods must not violate the License, introduce unsafe or harmful content,
   introduce malicious or deceptive behavior, bypass engine security, or
   impersonate official MultiPixel content.

c. All Mods require approval before they may be uploaded, shared,
   distributed, published, monetized, or used on any public Server. No Mod
   may bypass the approval system.

d. Mods must meet all technical requirements, including use of supported
   APIs, stable engine features, performance standards, safe threading,
   safe resource usage, and avoidance of deprecated functions, memory
   leaks, unauthorized file access, or any modification of protected
   systems.

e. Mods must meet all security requirements, including being free of
   malware, backdoors, unauthorized telemetry, obfuscated malicious code,
   or any behavior that weakens engine protections. Mods may not collect
   personal data, transmit data without disclosure, access external servers
   without approval, or modify security settings.

f. Mods must meet all content requirements, including avoidance of harmful,
   illegal, extremist, hateful, or deceptive content, and avoidance of any
   sexual content involving minors or unsafe gameplay mechanics.

g. Mods must meet all monetization requirements, including disclosure of
   all monetization methods, use of approved payment platforms, and
   avoidance of pay‑to‑win systems, gambling systems, or crypto/NFT
   monetization.

h. Mods must meet all data and telemetry requirements, including disclosure
   of all data collection, use of approved telemetry methods, compliance
   with retention and deletion rules, and avoidance of personal or
   sensitive data collection.

i. Mods must meet all safety requirements, including avoidance of harmful
   gameplay, unsafe mechanics, harassment systems, bypassing safety
   filters, or enabling predatory behavior.

j. Mods must meet all operational requirements, including maintaining
   stability, compatibility, documentation, update logs, versioning, and
   support for major engine updates. Mods must not cause crashes, data
   corruption, or intentional performance degradation.

k. Mods must meet all distribution requirements, including use of approved
   distribution channels and accurate descriptions, tags, warnings, and
   version information. Mods may not misrepresent features, hide
   monetization or data collection, or impersonate official content.

l. Violations of these requirements may result in removal from the Mod
   Marketplace, suspension of approval, monetization bans, delisting, legal
   action, or license termination.

m. Developers are strongly encouraged to use official MultiPixel inbuilt
   systems for data handling, telemetry, storage, transmission, and
   analytics. Third‑party systems may be approved only under strict
   conditions.

n. All Mods must comply with the latest version of the Mod Compliance
   Requirements.

27. Mod Content and Ethical Standards

a. All Mods must comply with all content and ethical standards established
   by MultiPixel. Mods must prioritize user safety, fairness, and
   non‑harmful content, and must not include illegal, extremist, hateful,
   abusive, deceptive, or otherwise harmful material.

b. The following content is strictly prohibited and constitutes an
   automatic severe violation: sexual content involving minors, child
   exploitation, real‑world illegal activity, doxxing or personal
   information, threats or targeted violence, extremist symbols or
   ideologies, hate speech, discriminatory content, harassment systems,
   stalking or tracking mechanics, forced interaction systems, mechanics
   that trap players without consent, simulated abuse, content encouraging
   self‑harm or dangerous behavior, manipulative or coercive mechanics,
   dark patterns, pay‑to‑win mechanics, gambling systems, crypto/NFT
   systems, malicious traps, malware, backdoors, unauthorized telemetry,
   hidden data collection, or obfuscation used to hide harmful behavior.

c. Restricted content may be allowed only with full review and explicit
   approval. Restricted content includes mature themes such as mild horror,
   mild violence, dark fantasy, or non‑graphic combat; non‑extremist
   political content; intense gameplay content such as high‑difficulty
   combat, survival mechanics, intense audio/visual effects, or jump
   scares; and competitive systems such as PvP, ranked systems, or
   competitive challenges. Restricted content may require warnings, opt‑in
   systems, accessibility options, or additional safety measures.

d. Allowed content includes cosmetic content, gameplay additions,
   quality‑of‑life features, and creative content, provided such content
   complies with all safety, data, monetization, and approval rules.

e. Mods must provide clear and accurate warnings for horror content,
   flashing lights, loud or sudden audio, mature themes, political content,
   or intense combat. Warnings must be visible, accurate, and honest.

f. Mods containing sensitive or intense content must require explicit
   player opt‑in, allow disabling sensitive features, and provide safe
   alternatives. Players must never be forced into disturbing content,
   political content, intense horror, or unsafe mechanics.

g. Mods used in multiplayer must not enable harassment, griefing, bypassing
   moderation, disabling safety filters, unlogged actions, or unfair
   advantages. For the purposes of this License, “logged actions” means
   actions recorded through the official MultiPixel Logging API or stored
   in logs that are accessible to MultiPixel upon request. Logging to
   private, hidden, encrypted, or developer‑controlled files that are not
   accessible to MultiPixel does not satisfy this requirement. Multiplayer
   Mods must respect server rules, moderation systems, and fairness
   requirements.

h. Violations of these content and ethical standards may result in removal
   from the Mod Marketplace, suspension of approval, permanent bans, legal
   action, or license termination.

i. Developers are strongly encouraged to use official MultiPixel inbuilt
   systems for data handling, telemetry, storage, transmission, and
   analytics. Third‑party systems may be approved only under strict
   conditions.

j. All Mods must comply with the latest version of the Mod Content and
   Ethical Standards.

28. Mod Data, Telemetry, and Privacy Requirements

a. All Mods must comply with all data, telemetry, and privacy requirements
   established by MultiPixel. Mods must follow the principles of minimal
   data collection, transparency, user protection, and secure handling of
   all approved data. Mods must not collect personal data, sensitive data,
   unauthorized telemetry, external tracking information, or transmit data
   without approval.

b. The following categories of data collection are strictly prohibited and
   constitute an automatic severe violation: personal data such as names,
   email addresses, phone numbers, physical addresses, social media
   accounts, or real‑world identity information; sensitive data such as
   age, gender, political views, religious beliefs, biometric data, or
   financial information; tracking or fingerprinting data such as hardware
   identifiers, IP addresses, device fingerprints, cross‑server tracking
   IDs, or behavioral fingerprints; payment data such as credit card
   numbers, bank information, or payment credentials; and any telemetry
   collected without disclosure or approval.

c. Mods may collect limited, non‑personal data only with explicit approval
   and only if fully disclosed. Allowed data includes gameplay data such as
   item usage, progression, statistics, and mod‑specific settings; technical
   data such as error logs, performance metrics, and compatibility
   information; and anonymized, non‑personal telemetry. All allowed data
   must be minimal, anonymized, disclosed, approved, and securely stored.

d. Mods must provide clear and accurate disclosures describing what data is
   collected, why it is collected, how it is used, how long it is stored,
   whether it is transmitted or shared, and whether collection is required
   or optional. Hidden or undisclosed data collection is a severe violation.

e. Mods must store all approved data securely, use encryption where
   applicable, avoid storing unnecessary data, follow retention limits, and
   delete data when no longer needed. Mods must not store data in plaintext,
   in public or unprotected locations, or for longer than necessary.

f. Mods must use only approved transmission methods, transmit only approved
   data, use secure connections, and disclose all transmission behavior.
   Mods must not transmit data secretly, transmit data to unknown or
   personal servers, or transmit data without approval.

g. Mods must define retention periods, delete data when no longer required,
   delete data upon user request where applicable, and delete all stored
   data when approval expires or the Mod is removed. Mods must not retain
   data indefinitely or after approval termination.

h. Mods interacting with multiplayer Servers must comply with all Server
   data rules and must not collect Server logs, Server metrics, player
   lists, chat logs, moderation data, or any information that monitors,
   tracks, or fingerprints players.

i. Developers must provide complete data documentation upon request,
   including data collection behavior, telemetry configuration, storage
   methods, transmission methods, retention policies, and deletion
   procedures. Refusal to provide data information is a severe violation.

j. Violations of these data, telemetry, and privacy requirements may result
   in removal from the Mod Marketplace, suspension of approval, permanent
   bans, legal action, or license termination.

k. Developers are strongly encouraged to use official MultiPixel inbuilt
   systems for data handling, telemetry, storage, transmission, and
   analytics. Third‑party systems may be approved only under strict
   conditions.

l. All Mods must comply with the latest version of the Mod Data, Telemetry,
   and Privacy Requirements.

29. Third‑Party Services, External Integrations, and External Transmission Rules

a. All Mods must comply with all rules governing third‑party services,
   external APIs, cloud platforms, analytics tools, SDKs, and any external
   integrations. Mods must not communicate with, transmit data to, or rely
   on any third‑party service except as explicitly disclosed and approved
   by MultiPixel.

b. Third‑party services are classified into categories including approved,
   conditional, restricted, and prohibited services. Mods may only use
   approved or conditionally approved services, and only for the purposes
   disclosed in the Mod submission. Use of prohibited services, including
   analytics platforms, advertising networks, fingerprinting services,
   personal data processors, unapproved cloud platforms, or any hidden or
   undisclosed service, is strictly forbidden.

c. Mods may only share minimal, non‑personal, non‑sensitive data with
   approved third‑party services, and only for the specific purpose
   disclosed and approved. Mods must not share personal data, sensitive
   data, IP addresses, device fingerprints, behavioral fingerprints,
   cross‑server identifiers, chat logs, moderation logs, authentication
   tokens, payment information, or any other prohibited data.

d. All third‑party services must be fully disclosed in the Mod submission,
   including service name, provider, purpose, data shared, storage
   behavior, transmission behavior, retention behavior, security measures,
   and risk assessment. Failure to disclose any third‑party service is a
   severe violation.

e. All third‑party integrations must follow strict security requirements,
   including encrypted transmission, secure authentication, least‑privilege
   access control, approved endpoints, and complete logging of all external
   transmissions. Mods must not use plaintext transmission, hardcoded
   secrets, dynamic DNS, hidden endpoints, or obfuscated domains.

f. Third‑party storage must comply with all MultiPixel data storage and
   retention rules. Only minimal gameplay or technical data may be stored
   externally, and only in encrypted form. Personal data, sensitive data,
   fingerprinting data, or any prohibited data may not be stored on any
   third‑party system.

g. All external transmissions must use approved endpoints, secure
   connections, and disclosed behavior. Mods must not transmit data
   secretly, transmit data to unknown or personal servers, use covert
   channels, or transmit any data that enables behavioral tracking or
   fingerprinting.

h. Third‑party services must follow strict retention and deletion rules,
   including defined retention periods, deletion upon Mod removal or
   approval revocation, and proof of deletion upon request. Retaining data
   beyond approved limits is prohibited.

i. All third‑party integrations are subject to routine, triggered, and
   forensic audits. Developers must provide complete documentation,
   including API documentation, endpoint lists, transmission logs, storage
   documentation, and security documentation. Refusal to cooperate with an
   audit is a severe violation.

j. If a third‑party service is breached, the developer must immediately
   report the breach, disable the integration, isolate the Mod, preserve
   logs, remediate the issue, and undergo a mandatory follow‑up audit.
   Failure to report or remediate a breach is a critical violation.

k. Violations of these third‑party rules may result in removal from the Mod
   Marketplace, suspension of approval, permanent bans, legal action,
   license termination, or penalties defined in the Governance Framework.

l. Developers are strongly encouraged to use official MultiPixel inbuilt
   systems for data handling, telemetry, storage, transmission, and
   analytics. Third‑party systems may be approved only under strict
   conditions.

m. All Mods must comply with the latest version of the Third‑Party
   Services, External Integrations, and External Transmission Rules.

30. Mod Monetization Requirements

a. All monetized Mods require explicit written approval from MultiPixel.
   No Mod may generate revenue of any kind without approval. Mod
   monetization must follow the principles of fairness, transparency,
   user protection, and non‑harmful design. Monetization must never
   introduce pay‑to‑win mechanics, gambling systems, crypto/NFT systems,
   deceptive practices, hidden monetization, or any form of data‑selling.

b. The following monetization methods may be approved if they comply with
   all safety, data, and fairness requirements: cosmetic sales including
   skins, textures, models, animations, sound packs, and cosmetic‑only
   items; content packs including new blocks, items, mobs, biomes,
   structures, and worldgen features; non‑competitive expansions including
   new gameplay systems, story content, or adventure content; voluntary
   donations and cosmetic‑only supporter perks; cosmetic or content‑access
   subscriptions; and sponsorships or brand partnerships that are fully
   disclosed and do not affect gameplay fairness.

c. The following monetization methods are strictly prohibited and
   constitute an automatic severe violation: pay‑to‑win systems including
   the sale of weapons, armor, stat boosts, progression, or competitive
   advantages; gambling systems including loot boxes, chance‑based rewards,
   slot‑machine mechanics, roulette mechanics, or gacha systems; crypto or
   NFT monetization including blockchain items, tokens, or crypto‑based
   progression; data monetization including the sale of user data,
   analytics, behavioral data, or tracking data; dark patterns including
   disguised purchases, forced purchases, manipulative UI, or misleading
   pricing; unapproved payment platforms or marketplaces; and any
   monetization conducted without explicit approval.

d. All monetized Mods must follow the official revenue share. Unless
   otherwise approved, MultiPixel receives thirty percent (30%) of all
   gross revenue and the developer receives seventy percent (70%). Voluntary
   donations that provide no perks incur no platform fee; donations that
   unlock cosmetic perks are subject to the standard revenue share. If a
   Mod enables monetization on a Server, both Mod and Server revenue share
   rules apply.

e. All monetized Mods must provide clear and accurate disclosures of all
   monetization methods, prices, subscription terms, sponsorships, data
   collection, and external services used. Disclosures must be visible,
   honest, and complete. Hidden monetization is a severe violation.

f. All transactions must use approved payment platforms, be logged
   accurately, stored securely, and remain fully auditable. Mods must not
   store payment data, process payments directly, or use insecure payment
   methods.

g. Monetized Mods must provide complete monetization documentation upon
   request, including transaction logs, revenue reports, payment platform
   logs, monetization configuration, and sponsorship agreements. Refusal to
   provide monetization data is a severe violation.

h. Violations of these monetization requirements may result in removal from
   the Mod Marketplace, suspension of monetization, permanent monetization
   bans, delisting, legal action, or license termination.

i. Developers are strongly encouraged to use official MultiPixel inbuilt
   systems for monetization, payment processing, and revenue reporting.
   Third‑party systems may be approved only under strict conditions.

j. All monetized Mods must comply with the latest version of the Mod
   Monetization Requirements.

31. Mod Violation Categories and Enforcement Classification

a. All Mod violations within the MultiPixel ecosystem are classified into
   three tiers: Minor Violations, Major Violations, and Severe Violations.
   These categories determine enforcement actions, penalties, audit
   requirements, and escalation procedures.

b. Minor Violations are low‑impact issues that do not threaten user safety,
   ecosystem integrity, or platform security. They typically involve
   unintentional mistakes such as incorrect metadata, missing tags,
   inaccurate descriptions, outdated submission materials, minor
   compatibility issues, small performance inefficiencies, missing content
   warnings, incomplete documentation, minor UI bugs, or non‑harmful
   scripting errors. Minor Violations must be corrected within a reasonable
   timeframe. Repeated Minor Violations may escalate to Major Violations.

c. Major Violations are significant issues that impact gameplay fairness,
   stability, transparency, or compliance, but do not involve malicious
   intent. Examples include hidden or unapproved monetization, unapproved
   data collection, misleading descriptions, significant performance
   degradation, unbalanced gameplay systems, unfair competitive advantages,
   bypassing minor safety systems, unauthorized external communication,
   failure to disclose sponsorships or telemetry, or distributing updates
   without approval. Major Violations require immediate correction and may
   result in temporary suspension, full review, or triggered audits.
   Repeated Major Violations may escalate to Severe Violations.

d. Severe Violations are the highest category and involve behavior that
   threatens user safety, platform security, legal compliance, or the
   integrity of the ecosystem. Severe Violations include malware,
   backdoors, unauthorized telemetry, data harvesting, personal data
   collection, extremist or hateful content, sexual content involving
   minors, gambling systems, crypto/NFT monetization, pay‑to‑win systems,
   bypassing engine security, code obfuscation used to hide harmful
   behavior, impersonating official MultiPixel content, distributing Mods
   without approval, attempting to bypass the approval or audit systems,
   tampering with platform infrastructure, or intentionally exploiting
   vulnerabilities. Severe Violations require immediate removal and may
   result in permanent bans, monetization revocation, legal action, license
   termination, and mandatory full audits.

e. Violations may escalate based on repeated offenses, refusal to fix
   issues, attempts to hide violations, user harm, security impact, or
   ecosystem impact. MultiPixel may reclassify any violation to a higher
   tier if warranted.

f. Developers are responsible for understanding all rules, maintaining
   compliance, updating Mods promptly, disclosing all changes, and
   cooperating fully with audits. Failure to cooperate may escalate any
   violation to a higher tier.

g. Enforcement actions may include warnings, suspensions, delisting,
   monetization bans, permanent bans, legal action, or license termination,
   as defined in the Governance Framework and Mod Penalty Tiers.

h. All Mods must comply with the latest version of the Mod Violation
   Categories and Enforcement Classification.

32. Mod Penalty Tiers and Enforcement Actions

a. All Mod violations are subject to the penalty system established by
   MultiPixel. Penalties are divided into three tiers—Minor, Major, and
   Severe—based on the severity of the violation, the risk posed to users
   or the ecosystem, and the developer’s compliance history.

b. Tier 1 (Minor Penalties) applies to Minor Violations that do not
   threaten user safety, platform security, or ecosystem integrity. Minor
   Violations include issues such as incorrect metadata, missing tags,
   inaccurate descriptions, minor compatibility issues, missing content
   warnings, incomplete documentation, minor UI bugs, or non‑harmful
   scripting errors. Penalties may include warning notices, required fixes
   within a set timeframe, temporary listing pauses, or required
   resubmission. Minor Violations may escalate to Tier 2 if repeated or
   left unaddressed.

c. Tier 2 (Major Penalties) applies to Major Violations that impact
   fairness, transparency, stability, or compliance but do not involve
   malicious intent. Major Violations include hidden or unapproved
   monetization, unapproved data collection, misleading descriptions,
   significant performance degradation, unbalanced gameplay systems,
   unauthorized external communication, failure to disclose telemetry or
   sponsorships, or distributing updates without approval. Penalties may
   include immediate suspension, temporary removal from the Mod
   Marketplace, forced rollback to a previous approved version,
   monetization freezes, mandatory audits, or probation periods. Major
   Violations may escalate to Tier 3 if repeated or if they cause user harm
   or ecosystem impact.

d. Tier 3 (Severe Penalties) applies to Severe Violations that threaten
   user safety, platform security, legal compliance, or the integrity of
   the ecosystem. Severe Violations include malware, backdoors,
   unauthorized telemetry, data harvesting, personal data collection,
   extremist or hateful content, sexual content involving minors, gambling
   systems, crypto/NFT monetization, pay‑to‑win systems, bypassing engine
   security, code obfuscation used to hide harmful behavior, impersonating
   official MultiPixel content, distributing Mods without approval,
   bypassing the approval or audit systems, tampering with platform
   infrastructure, or intentionally exploiting vulnerabilities. Penalties
   may include immediate removal, permanent Mod bans, permanent developer
   bans, permanent monetization bans, revocation of all approvals, full
   ecosystem audits, legal action, or license termination. Severe
   Violations are subject to zero tolerance.

e. Penalties may apply to the developer account, not only the Mod. Account‑
   level penalties may include probation, temporary suspension, permanent
   suspension, permanent bans, removal of all Mods, or revocation of all
   monetization rights. Account penalties may be imposed when multiple Mods
   violate rules, when violations repeat, or when the developer acts
   maliciously or attempts to bypass enforcement.

f. Monetization penalties may include monetization freezes, monetization
   suspensions, permanent monetization bans, revenue clawbacks in cases of
   fraud, or removal from the Mod Marketplace.

g. Audit‑related penalties may include immediate suspension of all Mods,
   forced removal from the marketplace, permanent bans, or legal action if
   the developer refuses to cooperate with audits or attempts to obstruct
   audit processes.

h. Violations escalate automatically based on severity, repetition, intent,
   user harm, ecosystem impact, or developer cooperation. MultiPixel may
   reclassify any violation to a higher tier if warranted.

i. Developers may appeal Tier 1 and Tier 2 penalties. Tier 3 penalties are
   not eligible for appeal except in cases of proven error.

j. All Mods must comply with the latest version of the Mod Penalty Tiers
   and Enforcement Actions.

33. Mod Safety Standards and User Protection Requirements

a. All Mods must comply with all safety standards established by MultiPixel.
   Mods must prioritize user safety, fairness, transparency, and non‑harmful
   gameplay. Mods must not endanger users, enable predatory behavior,
   introduce harmful mechanics, encourage harassment or abuse, or include
   illegal or extremist content.

b. The following content and behavior are strictly prohibited and constitute
   an automatic severe violation: sexual content involving minors, extremist
   content, hate speech, targeted harassment, doxxing or personal
   information, threats or violence against real individuals, mechanics that
   encourage self‑harm, mechanics that simulate abuse, mechanics that enable
   predatory behavior, mechanics that trap or isolate players without
   consent, psychological manipulation including fear‑based coercion,
   forced participation in disturbing content, deceptive or manipulative UI,
   dark patterns, and real‑world extremist political content.

c. Certain content is allowed only with full review and explicit approval.
   Restricted content includes mature themes such as mild horror, mild
   violence, or dark fantasy; non‑extremist political content including
   fictional political systems or educational political references; and
   competitive gameplay systems such as PvP, combat mechanics, or
   competitive challenges. Restricted content must not encourage harassment,
   create unfair advantages, or enable bullying or abuse, and may require
   warnings, opt‑in systems, or additional safety measures.

d. Mods must include appropriate safety mechanisms. Mods must provide clear
   and accurate warnings for mature themes, horror content, flashing lights,
   loud or sudden audio, intense combat, or political content. Mods
   containing sensitive content must require explicit opt‑in, allow players
   to disable sensitive features, and provide safe alternatives. Mods must
   respect parental controls, age restrictions, and content filters.

e. Mods used in multiplayer environments must prevent harassment, abuse,
   griefing, exploitation, and unfair advantages. Mods must not bypass
   server moderation, disable safety filters, enable unlogged actions, or
   create unmoderated communication channels.

f. Mods must comply with all data safety requirements, including avoiding
   personal or sensitive data collection, disclosing all telemetry, using
   approved data systems, following retention and deletion rules, and
   avoiding tracking or fingerprinting users. Mods must not store data
   insecurely or transmit data without approval.

g. Mods must comply with all technical safety requirements, including
   avoiding crashes, data corruption, unsafe memory usage, infinite loops,
   excessive CPU/GPU usage, unsafe threading, or unauthorized file access.
   Mods must not modify engine binaries, bypass sandboxing, inject harmful
   code, or weaken security systems.

h. Mods must comply with all community safety requirements, including
   avoiding mechanics that encourage harassment, bullying, discrimination,
   exploitation, or unsafe behavior. Mods must promote fair play and
   respectful interaction.

i. Developers must provide safety documentation upon request, including
   content warnings, gameplay descriptions, data collection details, and
   risk assessments where applicable. Refusal to provide safety information
   is a severe violation.

j. Violations of these safety standards may result in removal from the Mod
   Marketplace, suspension of approval, permanent bans, legal action, or
   license termination, as defined in the Mod Violation Categories and Mod
   Penalty Tiers.

k. All Mods must comply with the latest version of the Mod Safety Standards
   and User Protection Requirements.


